article.headline: Kirilenko scores 25
article.linkText: Jazz, undefeated at home, beat Grizzlies 96-89
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Utah Jazz have been waiting more than two years to see what Raul Lopez can do in the NBA. They found out Saturday night. Lopez, the point guard from Spain who was drafted in the first round of the 2001 draft, scored 10 points of his 12 points in a key run and the Jazz defeated the Memphis Grizzlies 96-89. "It felt good to find my game because I feel like I'm starting over. I'm happy to be a basketball player again," said Lopez, who has rehabilitated from two major knee surgeries since he was drafted. Andrei Kirilenko had 25 points, but it was Lopez who triggered the comeback to keep Utah undefeated at home. Utah trailed 70-65 late in the third quarter when Lopez came in for Carlos Arroyo. The 6-foot guard sparked the Jazz to nine consecutive points, hitting a layup and passing to Raja Bell for a 3-pointer before the end of the period. Early in the fourth, Lopez scored eight straight points for the Jazz, including a spectacular left-handed running hook to beat the shot clock as Utah increased its lead to 88-79 with 5:49 to play. "I have been struggling lately but I always have confidence in my shot. I believe I can make them when they need me," Lopez said. After missing Utah's loss at Golden State on Friday because of his grandmother's funeral, Matt Harpring returned and scored 14 points. DeShawn Stevenson added 13. James Posey scored a season-high 17 points, Mike Miller had 16 and Jason Williams added 14 points and 11 assists for the Grizzlies, who lost their third straight on their Western road trip. "It was a tough loss. We had the game under control for the most part and we just couldn't get the job done," said Pau Gasol, who had 13 points and 12 rebounds. Utah's inexperience showed down the stretch. The Jazz went scoreless for 3:45 while Miller scored four points in a 6-0 run that cut the lead to 88-85 with 2:29 to play. In the final minute, Miller tried to get the Grizzlies within two when he made a determined drive. But Bell drew a charge, and Kirilenko sealed the win with two free throws on the other end. "Bell did a terrific job. He had his hands on the basketball so many times it was fun to watch," Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. The Jazz can't rely on the John Stockton and Karl Malone pick-and-roll anymore in crunch time, so they use crisp passing and lots of cutting to get open shots. They also used a lot of Lopez darting through the defense and finding a shot or an open man. "Lopez did a terrific job for them," Memphis coach Hubie Brown said. "He broke us down. He broke us down a lot when they had nothing going." Both teams lost Friday night, and the tired players were sloppy, with a lot of missed layups and 37 combined turnovers. But Lopez was sure-handed with no turnovers and four assists. "Raul had a nice performance. He's starting to look a little like John Stockton," Kirilenko said. That's the last thing Lopez wants to hear. "It's hard to play with comparisons to Stockton. He was the best point guard ever in the NBA. I can only be me," Lopez said. The Jazz now face four straight games on the road, where they have not won this season.

Game notes
Keon Clark, who has played just two games for Utah, was placed on the injured list before the game. He is expected to be out six weeks after surgery to remove a bone spur in his right ankle. Rookie center. Curtis Borchardt was activated and blocked a shot in his first NBA minute. ... Memphis forward Theron Smith also played his first NBA game after missing the first five games with knee tendinitis. ... Miller limped off in the final minute after twisting his ankle while going for a loose ball. He's day-to-day. ... After Brown complained about a no-call, official Tony Brothers turned with a perplexed expression and said, "You have something to say every time."
